I. Context and description of the data:¶

Background information on the subject and the field of study¶

The data set that we chose to work with is the World Happiness Report. This report is a survey of the state of global happiness. The hapiness scores and rankings use data from the Gallup World Poll. The scores are based on the main life evaluation question asked in the poll. In the question, respondents are asked to think of a ladder with the best possible life for them being a 10 and the worst possible life being a 0 and then to rate how they view their own life. 159 countries are included in this report.

The other variables in the data set are:

  • country
  • region
  • economic production
  • social support
  • life expectancy
  • freedom
  • absense of corruption
  • generosity

These columns describe the extent to which these factors contribute in evaluating the happiness in each country. The scoring comes from how the variable in the country compares to the benchmark value of the dystopian society. Dystopia is an imaginary country with the world's least happy people. They have the lowest incomes, life expectancy, etc.

Information on data collection¶

a) Who collected the data:

This data set uses date from the Gallup World poll. The scores are based on answers to the main life evaluation question asked in the poll. [1]

b) When the data was collection:

This data was collected in 2015. However, it is an annual report. [1]

c) How the data was collected:

Gallup data is collected either via a one on one interview in developing countries and phone interviews in areas where telephone coverage represents at least 80% of the population. [2]

d) Any implications this may have on analysis:

Considering only some people have the time and resources to complete a 30 minute phone interview, there may be sample biases in place. Additionally, it does not represent the population below the age of 15, so adolescent happiness is not taken into account. However, the Gallup poll is a very thorough and credible measure of world populations and the final forecasts are typically within 2.25 percentage points of the true value. [2]

Explanation of the dystopian variable¶

To be able to to interpret the results of the linear regressions, it is important to understand where the scoring is coming from. The baseline to which countries are compared is a dytopian society. The dystopian society is a combination of the worst scoring countries across all of the variables. For example, if the United States had the worst ecomomy in the world, the dytopian society would take take on the economy of the United States, and so on for each category. Every other country's economy would be scored on how much better it was than that of the United State's, hence all of the scores are positive for all categories and all countries.

To illustrate this further, we took a look at which aspects from which countries make up the dystopian socitey.

From above, we can see that there is an R-squared of 90.9%, showing that 90.9% of the variance is explained by the economy. We also see that the p-value for the Economy variable is approximately 0.000 (or 1.85e-83), which is less than 0.05. Economy is an incredibly significant predictor when wanting to predict the happiness of a country.

The Model looks like this: Happiness Score = 3.4988 + 2.2182*(Economy (GDP per Capita))

  • Bo: When the economy score is zero (the lowest scoring country), we expect the average happiness score to be 3.4988
  • B1: If all else is kept constant and we increase the economy score by one unit, we expect the happiness score to increase by 2.2182

Summary of modeling¶

We found that overall all of the variables in each of the simple linear regressions were significant, although the generosity variable was the least significant predictor. This means that the perceived generosity level of the people in the country is not as important for determining how happy a country is. It makes sense that all of them would be significant because they help determine the happiness level, although we were hypothesizing that generosity would not be based off of the correlation coefficient (a correlation coefficient of 0.18). Overall, though, we can see that the trust, generosity, freedom, health, family value, and economic status of a country are all significant predictors when predicting the happiness level of a country.
